{
  "text_segment": "A chapter having been read through twice, the books were closed and the girls examined. The lesson had been on the reign of Charles I, and there were sundry questions about tonnage and poundage and ship-money, which most of us passed over slipshod or in absolute silence. But Helen Burns, when once called upon, answered every question with an accuracy and readiness that showed she had made a thorough study of the subject. I had anticipated for her a meed of commendation, but what was my surprise when, instead of praise, Miss Scatcherd exclaimed sharply, 'You dirty, disagreeable girl! you have never cleaned your nails this morning!' Helen made no reply. I could have eagerly explained that the water in the pitchers was frozen that morning, but I stood silent. My attention was then called off by Miss Smith, who, wanting help in the formation of a new work-bag, had called me to her. When I returned to my seat, I found Miss Scatcherd's group had broken up, but I saw her order Helen to go and fetch 'the rod'—a bundle of twigs tied together. With a curtsy, Helen brought the instrument of punishment. Without a word, she untied the pinafore which protected her frock, and stood prepared. Miss Scatcherd seized the rod, and administered an infinity of strokes, dealt with the severity of a fury. Not a tear rose to Helen's eye; and while I writhed with impotent rage, she received the strokes, and returned to her place. 'A hardened girl!' remarked Miss Scatcherd; 'nothing can correct you of your slatternly habits.' As she passed me, I saw her discreetly draw her handkerchief from her pocket and press it to her eyes, wiping away a single tear."
}
